.ie \n(.g .ds Aq \(aq
.el .ds Aq '
.TH server 1  "server " 
.SH NAME
server \- Start debug server for remote connections
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBserver\fR [\fB\-p\fR|\fB\-\-port\fR] [\fB\-t\fR|\fB\-\-token\fR] [\fB\-\-tls\-cert\fR] [\fB\-\-tls\-key\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] 
.SH DESCRIPTION
Start debug server for remote connections
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-port\fR \fI<PORT>\fR [default: 9229]
Port to listen on
.TP
\fB\-t\fR, \fB\-\-token\fR \fI<TOKEN>\fR
Authentication token (optional, if not provided no auth required)
.TP
\fB\-\-tls\-cert\fR \fI<TLS_CERT>\fR
TLS certificate file path (optional)
.TP
\fB\-\-tls\-key\fR \fI<TLS_KEY>\fR
TLS private key file path (optional)
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help
.SH SIGNALS
.TP
\fBSIGINT\fR (Ctrl+C)
Gracefully shuts down the server, closes the listener socket, and rejects new connections.
.TP
\fBSIGTERM\fR
Gracefully shuts down the server on Unix/Linux systems.
.SH SHUTDOWN BEHAVIOR
When the server receives a shutdown signal (SIGINT or SIGTERM):
.IP \(bu 2
The listener socket is closed immediately
.IP \(bu 2
New connection attempts are rejected
.IP \(bu 2
Existing client connections complete their active requests
.IP \(bu 2
All resources are released
.IP \(bu 2
The process exits cleanly with exit code 0
.SH EXAMPLES
Start a basic debug server:
.RS
.nf
$ soroban-debug server --port 9229
.fi
.RE
.PP
Start a token-protected server:
.RS
.nf
$ soroban-debug server --port 9229 --token "random-32-byte-token"
.fi
.RE
.PP
Start with TLS encryption:
.RS
.nf
$ soroban-debug server --port 9229 \\
  --token "random-token" \\
  --tls-cert /etc/soroban/cert.pem \\
  --tls-key /etc/soroban/key.pem
.fi
.RE
.PP
Gracefully shutdown a running server:
.RS
.nf
$ kill -SIGTERM $SERVER_PID
.fi
.RE
